";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1554404959;}i:6;a:13:{s:5:"title";s:73:"Jamie Dimon or Warren Buffett: Who writes the longer shareholder letters?";s:4:"link";s:102:"https://qz.com/1587731/jamie-dimon-or-warren-buffett-who-writes-the-longer-annual-shareholder-letters/";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 04 Apr 2019 19:04:39 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Jason Karaian";}s:8:"category";s:167:"Uncategorizedannual lettersBerkshire HathawayCEOsFinanceinvestinginvestor relationsinvestorsJamie DimonJPMorganJPMorgan Chaseleadersshareholder lettersUSwarren buffett";s:4:"guid";s:24:"https://qz.com/1587731//";s:11:"description";s:148:"When it comes to expansive letters to shareholders, the financier who immediately comes to mind is not necessarily Dimon (despite his best efforts).";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3530:"<img width="1024" height="575" src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTX2RDBR-e1554403713134.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1024" class="attachment-medium_10 size-medium_10 wp-post-image" alt="JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie DImon" /><p>JPMorgan boss Jamie Dimon published his <a href="https://www.jpmorganchase.com/corporate/investor-relations/document/ceo-letter-to-shareholders-2018.pdf">annual letter to shareholders</a> (pdf) today. The musings of the CEO of the largest bank in the US by assets are always closely followed. People who turned to the letter today got a window into Dimon’s thoughts on banking, business, regulation, markets, politics…</p>
<p>… <em>deep breath …</em></p>
<p>… artificial intelligence, cyber security, infrastructure, capitalism, socialism …</p>
<p>…<em> another breath …</em></p>
<p><em>… </em>diversity, innovation, taxes, immigration, the military…</p>
<div id="attachment_1587743" style="width: 330px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1587743" class="size-hero-s wp-image-1587743" src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/JPMorgan-letter-2018-first-page.png?w=320" alt="" width="320" height="435" srcset="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/JPMorgan-letter-2018-first-page.png 520w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/JPMorgan-letter-2018-first-page.png?resize=50,68 50w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/JPMorgan-letter-2018-first-page.png?resize=160,218 160w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/JPMorgan-letter-2018-first-page.png?resize=320,435 320w" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px" /><p id="caption-attachment-1587743" class="wp-caption-text"><!-- caption placeholder --></p></div>
<p>Suffice it to say, it’s a long letter—more than 26,000 words over 50 pages, to be precise.</p>
<p>Dimon has been getting wordier over time: after taking over the bank in 2005, his first few letters ran to a dozen pages or so. Those mostly stuck to the business of banking, with some generic asides about JPMorgan being a good corporate citizen. Lately, Dimon’s annual letters wax lyrical about “America’s role on the world stage” and the like.</p>
<p>When it comes to expansive letters to shareholders, the financier who immediately comes to mind is usually <em>not</em> Dimon (despite his best efforts), but rather Berkshire Hathaway’s Warren Buffett. The “Oracle of Omaha” has been spinning folksy wisdom about business, investing, and life in the shareholder letters he&#8217;s been publishing for <a href="http://www.berkshirehathaway.com/letters/letters.html">more than 50 years</a>. The letters are traditionally pored over by investors <a href="https://seekingalpha.com/article/4249327-underrated-lessons-warren-buffetts-2018-shareholder-letter">looking for tips</a> and by analysts searching for clues about <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/warren-buffetts-next-acquisition-could-be-target-or-carmax-says-credit-suisse.html">Buffett’s next move</a>.</p>
<p>Buffett’s <a href="http://www.berkshirehathaway.com/letters/2018ltr.pdf">latest letter</a> (pdf) ran to a brisk 14 pages. His longest was a 37-pager in 2014, marking his 50th anniversary of taking over the company. It was <em>almost</em> as long as Dimon’s that year, but not quite.</p>
