mp;strip=all&amp;w=1024" class="attachment-medium_10 size-medium_10 wp-post-image" alt="" srcset="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg 4566w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=768,432 768w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=50,28 50w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=160,90 160w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=320,180 320w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=640,360 640w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=940,529 940w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/CATL-aerial.jpg?resize=1600,900 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" />In 2017, only six years after it was founded, CATL became the world’s largest electric-vehicle battery supplier, beating out stalwarts like Panasonic, LG, and Samsung&hellip;";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1554364810;}i:27;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:73:"Google Doodle is honoring Hugh Masekela, the father of South African jazz";s:4:"link";s:94:"https://qz.com/africa/1587284/google-doodle-honors-hugh-masekela-father-of-south-african-jazz/";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 04 Apr 2019 07:35:45 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Yinka Adegoke";}s:8:"category";s:89:"Uncategorized#HughMasekela80thAfricaHugh MasekelaJazzMiles DavisMiriam MakebaSouth Africa";s:4:"guid";s:24:"https://qz.com/1587284//";s:11:"description";s:123:"Masekela performed alongside musicians such as Miriam Makeba, Miles Davis, Abdullah Ibrahim, Fela Kuti and Harry Belafonte.";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:4570:"<img width="1024" height="635" src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1024" class="attachment-medium_10 size-medium_10 wp-post-image" alt="" srcset="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg 2048w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=768,476 768w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=50,31 50w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=160,99 160w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=320,198 320w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=640,397 640w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=940,582 940w, https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTR8M8Y.jpg?resize=1600,991 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><p>For what would have been his 80th birthday, Google Doodle is honoring Hugh Masekela, the trumpeter and bandleader fondly remembered as the father of South African jazz.</p>
<p>Masekela, who died on Jan. 23, 2018 after a battle with prostate cancer, was more than a musician. He was also a leading activist during his country&#8217;s rule under the repressive apartheid government. He ended up in exile for 31 years and did not return home until the release of Nelson Mandela from prison in 1990. But during his exile, he kept playing and raising awareness about the conditions in his country and around the world.</p>
<p>Born on April 4, 1939, Masekela first picked up a trumpet after seeing the film <em>Young Man With a Horn</em> and encouraged by activist Father Trevor Huddleston. Often described as the “father of South African jazz,” Masekela was an icon of South Africa’s <a href="http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/destruction-sophiatown" rel="noopener">Sophiatown</a>, the political and cultural enclave of Johannesburg that was razed by apartheid police but remains a symbol of black freedom.</p>
<div id="attachment_1587335" style="width: 457px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-1587335" class="wp-image-1587335 size-hero-l" src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Screen-Shot-2019-04-04-at-3.49.37-AM-e1554364582934.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=447" alt="" width="447" height="236" /><p id="caption-attachment-1587335" class="wp-caption-text">Hugh Masekela&#8217;s Google doodle on Apr. 4 2019, which would have been his 80th birthday</p></div>
<p>His birthday anniversary doodle is available in South Africa, the US, UK, and a few other countries. It is also being marked on social media with the hashtag #HughMasekela80th.</p>
<p class="a1dbe africa">In a career that <a href="http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/hugh-masekela">spanned decades</a>, Masekela performed alongside musicians such as Miriam Makeba, Miles Davis, Abdullah Ibrahim, Fela Kuti, and Harry Belafonte. Like his contemporaries, Masekela’s performance was closely tied to his political beliefs. His music became the backdrop to the struggle against apartheid, with anthems like <em><a href="https://youtu.be/NG3oKb2JQow">Bring Back Nelson Mandela</a> </em>and <em><a href="https://youtu.be/gj1Lug-U38I">Soweto Blues</a>.</em></p>
<p class="a1dbe africa">Masekela’s last public performance was scheduled for November last year alongside Zimbabwean musical legend Oliver Mtukudzi and a host of young musicians, but was forced to cancel due to ill health. Sadly, <a href="https://qz.com/africa/1534462/oliver-mtukudzi-was-our-gift-from-zimbabwe-to-the-world/">Mtukudzi himself died</a> almost exactly a year later in January this year.</p>
<p class="_21349 africa none _4ca8e"><strong>Read next: <a href="https://qz.com/africa/1186791/hugh-masekela-listen-to-how-the-legendary-musician-reinvented-his-sound-through-decades-of-collaborations/">Listen to how Hugh Masekela reinvented his sound through decades of collaborations</a></strong></p>
<p class="_21349 africa none _4ca8e"><strong>Read next: <a href="https://qz.com/africa/1266651/the-best-anthem-for-workers-day-is-hugh-masekelas-tale-about-apartheids-migrant-labour-system/">The best anthem for Workers’ Day is Hugh Masekela’s tale about apartheid’s migrant labor system</a></strong></p>
