";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1554353054;}i:37;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:92:"Mumbai residents have the fastest-growing salaries in India but still can’t afford a house";s:4:"link";s:93:"https://qz.com/india/1587136/mumbai-home-rates-are-so-high-that-a-salary-hike-cant-help-much/";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 04 Apr 2019 04:10:25 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:11:"Kuwar Singh";}s:8:"category";s:231:"Uncategorizedbank loanbengaluruBombayChennaiDelhi NCRhome loanhome ownershiphousehold incomehousinghousing affordabilityhousing marketHyderabadincome‪India‬JLLJLL IndiaKolkataMumbainew delhi ncrPunereal estateresidential market";s:4:"guid";s:24:"https://qz.com/1587136//";s:11:"description";s:38:"The situation won't ease even in 2021.";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2895:"<img width="1024" height="576" src="https://cms.qz.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/RTX6IA4H-e1554340986332.jpg?quality=80&amp;strip=all&amp;w=1024" class="attachment-medium_10 size-medium_10 wp-post-image" alt="mumbai-housing-apartment-home-loan" /><p>Household incomes in India&#8217;s financial capital are rising the fastest. Yet, most families there can&#8217;t afford a home.</p>
<p>Mumbai is an exception among big Indian cities where home ownership has become largely affordable, according to JLL India.</p>
<p>On April 01, the real estate services firm released its <a href="https://www.jll.co.in/content/dam/jll-com/documents/pdf/research/apac/india/jll-home-purchase-affordability-index-2019.pdf">home purchase affordability index</a>, which shows that the average annual household income in Mumbai falls 16% short of the minimum income required to qualify for a bank loan on a 1,000-square-feet apartment at prevailing market prices.</p>
<p>This is primarily due to Mumbai&#8217;s sky-high real estate prices. A property of the same size is more expensive in the coastal city than elsewhere, forcing families to apply for bigger loans that require a higher level of minimum income for eligibility.</p>
<div class="atlas-chart" data-id="ryEvuTMKE" data-width="640" data-height="449"><img src="https://www.theatlas.com/i/atlas_ryEvuTMKE.png" style="max-width: 100%; min-width:100%;"></div>
<p>(<em>The above chart shows how much higher or lower the average annual household income in a city is compared to the minimum income required to qualify for a home loan on a 1,000-square-feet apartment at the prevailing market prices.</em>)</p>
<p>In 2013, Hyderabad had been the only major city where average household income was above the minimum eligibility criterion for a home loan. As incomes have grown faster than residential prices since then, all except Mumbai have an affordable housing market today.</p>
<div class="atlas-chart" data-id="HJ4gdRMY4" data-width="640" data-height="449"><img src="https://www.theatlas.com/i/atlas_HJ4gdRMY4.png" style="max-width: 100%; min-width:100%;"></div>
<p>Incidentally, Mumbai&#8217;s household income growth rate has been the highest. This has had a major positive impact on the ability of families to take out home loans: In 2013, the average household in Mumbai was earning just 47% of the minimum income required to qualify for a home loan, as compared to 84% today.</p>
<p>Yet, home ownership will not become a reality for a majority of the city&#8217;s households till at least 2021, JLL said.</p>
<p>According to the 2011 census, with 18.4 million residents, Mumbai is India&#8217;s most populous metropolitan region. It is <a href="https://qz.com/india/1396785/drone-photos-capture-the-staggering-inequality-in-mumbai/">also home to</a> one of Asia&#8217;s biggest slums, alongside some of the continent&#8217;s priciest real estate.</p>
